I might want to give up a hundred times,
but I will stand up for the 101st time and try to move forward.

I’m under enormous pressure. I’ve wasted most of the time I had left, yet I still can’t bring myself to start. But at least, under this pressure, I’ve developed a study routine that I believe is highly efficient.

First, if I can’t understand the exam paper, I learn whichever words I don’t know. After memorizing one paper thoroughly, I can understand at least eighty percent of the next one. Right now I’m only studying Statistics, but I believe this method works perfectly well for my other subjects too.

Take a photo of the first page of the exam paper, use Doubao to extract all the statistics terms, and skim them twice just to get a general impression. Do only 3 to 5 questions at a time, not the entire set.
For each question: take a photo and translate it. If I have an idea how to solve it, I work it out; if not, I look at the key concepts and the answer.
The crucial step: after reviewing the concepts and answer, close everything and redo the question entirely on my own — even if it’s just writing down a few numbers.
After finishing those 3–5 questions, immediately go to Khan Academy and watch videos only on the topics covered in those few questions, not the whole chapter.
Repeat steps 1 and 2 until the entire exam paper is completed.
Once finished, quickly go through the corresponding chapter on Khan Academy at 1.5x speed, focusing especially on the parts I got stuck on earlier.
Find new questions — or questions on the same topics from the same set — and practice again. If using the same paper, I recommend covering the answers and redoing them.
Finally, formally memorize all the terms I encountered while solving the questions.

At first, I deeply regretted turning down those excellent teachers. With their help, I probably would have gotten a 5 long ago, instead of wasting time here while feeling anxious. But I’ve always known that the essence of education is self-study. What I need is the ability to learn anything I want entirely on my own. So even though I only have a few days left, I’m still willing to try.

There is a book by W. Somerset Maugham whose title and message fit my current thoughts perfectly: My Heart Wants a More Adventurous Life. The quote goes: It does not make me anxious at all to find that my opinions differ from those of most people. I still have some faith in my own intuition.
